WindowsHelp
                   WINDOWS                        01
                                                  02
The windows used to display graphs can be resized,03
moved around, added and deleted, and the contents 04
can be changed.                                   05
Clicking on a graph with the mouse brings up the  06
input screen to allow you to change the graph     07
contents or the graph scales.                     08
Clicking on the numerical window allows you to    09
change the variables that are displayed           10
numericlaly.                                      11
The options under WINDOW also allow you to change 12
the graph contents and the numerical window       13
contents, but also allow you to move windows      14
around the screen.  The generic 2-window and      15
4-window options load commonly used formats.      16
                                                  17
When you select 'Modify Window Layout' you are    18
asked to select the window to modify.  This can   19
be done with the mouse or moving through the      20
windows with the arrow keys.  The selected window 21
can then be moved, resized, deleted or copied.    22
When you are finished with this window, you are   23
asked to select another window.  Type Escape when 24
you are finished modifying windows.               25

SaveConfigHelp
            SAVE CONFIGURATION                    01
                                                  02
You are about to save the current configuration   03
to a file.  A configuration consists of the window04
layout, the initial values of the dynamical       05
variables, the current values of the force        06
parameters and the numerical integration parmeters07
                                                  08
You should modify the User-Defined Help screen    09
before you save this file by selecting 'Modify    10
User-defined Help' under FILE.  The user-defined  11
help screen should be a reminder as to what is    12
special about this particular configuration.      13
                                                  14
Note that a configuration file is specific to     15
a particular force (as defined through the Pascal 16
programs).  When loading a new configuration file 17
all such files are displayed.  Thus, you should   18
choose a name that will help identify this file   19
with the current force.                           20
                                                  21
Note that you can load any configuration file for 22
any force, but certain graphs, or parameter values23
may not make sense if the configuration file does 24
not apply to that force.                          25

